{"type":"item.started","item":{"id":"item_7","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc \"cat > .workflow/iphone-app-factory/spec-red-team.md <<'EOF'\n# Spec Red Team Review: WakeTask\n\n## Scope of review\n- Reviewed \"'`.workflow/iphone-app-factory/spec.md`\n- Reviewed `.workflow/iphone-app-factory/definition-of-done.md`\n- Reviewed `.workflow/iphone-app-factory/research-synthesis.md`\n- Reviewed `.workflow/iphone-app-factory/quality-bar.json`\n\n## Verdict basis against reject criteria\n\n### 1) Research evidence strength\n- Decision: **Pass with caveat**\n- Why:\n  - Evidence sources match required breadth (App Store reviews, Reddit, competitors, iOS design references).\n  - Synthesis shows coherent cross-source signal: reliability distrust, autopilot dismissal, ad friction, relapse after dismissal.\n  - Limitation is explicitly disclosed: App Store scraping partial and Mobbin session-gated.\n- Red-team note:\n  - Confidence is appropriately stated as medium-high, not overstated; limitation transparency reduces integrity risk.\n\n### 2) Feature clarity and testability\n- Decision: **Pass**\n- Why:\n  - Spec defines concrete FR/NFR items (`FR-01..FR-06`, `NFR-01..NFR-06`) with explicit verification methods.\n  - DoD includes traceability requirement (`DoD-02`) and release-blocking evidence expectations.\n  - Core differentiators are measurable (`D-01..D-04`) and tied to flow visibility.\n- Red-team note:\n  - “Representative coverage of all reachable MVP screens” in Appium pass criteria should eventually be converted to a quantized threshold in implementation docs, but current language is still auditable.\n\n### 3) Template-likeness / App Store 4.3 clone risk\n- Decision: **Pass (guarded)**\n- Why:\n  - Differentiation thesis is not a generic “alarm + puzzle” claim; it is a closed-loop behavior system: reliability ledger + wake contract + adaptive anti-autopilot + first-task bridge.\n  - Spec includes explicit 4.3 hardening checks on onboarding/core flow/store narrative and anti-generic metadata copy.\n  - Non-goals avoid drifting into commodity “wellness app” template territory.\n- Red-team note:\n  - Risk remains at execution level if screenshots/metadata regress to generic challenge-alarm language; gate is correctly present to prevent this.\n\n### 4) Boilerplate reuse clarity\n- Decision: **Pass**\n- Why:\n  - Reuse policy is explicit: extend `SwiftAIBoilerplatePro`, “extend before replace,” and forbid platform rebuilds without ADR-level justification.\n  - Quality bar and DoD reinforce this with blocking review evidence (`DoD-03`).\n\n### 5) Appium exploratory QA requirement\n- Decision: **Pass**\n- Why:\n  - Appium evidence artifact path is mandatory and release-blocking.\n  - Pass fields and conditions are explicitly enumerated.\n  - Deferral policy is constrained by two required conditions (explicit input + documented blocker), matching quality-bar prohibition against silent skipping.\n\n### 6) macOS/Xcode release evidence requirement\n- Decision: **Pass**\n- Why:\n  - Both `xcodebuild build` and `xcodebuild test` are mandatory in spec, DoD (`DoD-04`, `DoD-05`), and quality bar.\n  - Quality bar explicitly forbids claiming iOS validation complete without macOS/GitHub Actions evidence.\n\n## Cross-functional skepticism summary\n- Product: Positioning is differentiated and problem-backed; strongest risk is overpromising reliability beyond iOS platform limits, which the spec already flags.\n- QA: Acceptance criteria are generally testable and tied to artifacts; Appium and static gates are properly release-blocking.\n- iOS architecture: Reuse and anti-rebuild constraints are clear and enforceable.\n- App Store review: 4.3 anti-clone strategy is present and materially stronger than a cosmetic reskin approach.\n\n## Remaining non-blocking risks to track during implementation\n- Ensure reliability wording in product copy never exceeds platform-verifiable guarantees.\n- Convert “representative Appium coverage” into 